The '''Brother ADS-2000 high speed document scanner''' is a Linux-compatible USB document scanner.<ref>AI-generated by Antigravity on 2026-06-15</ref>

== Installation ==
You will need the 32-bit or 64-bit `.deb` file from Brother. Install '''[[gscan2pdf]]''' first for some dependencies.

The required driver files have been archived to Google Drive:
* '''brscan4''' (32-bit): brscan4-0.4.2-1.i386.deb<ref>Google Drive: [https://drive.google.com/file/d/1vPmyhwkcHwBiRg4QKdBYJjsOJaMHlorx/view?usp=drivesdk brscan4-0.4.2-1.i386.deb] retrieved 2026-06-15</ref>
* '''brscan4''' (64-bit): brscan4-0.4.11-1.amd64.deb<ref>Google Drive: [https://drive.google.com/file/d/1v2hybPBbz1QTR68HQ3hEpfrO-ewWNvG_/view?usp=drivesdk brscan4-0.4.11-1.amd64.deb] retrieved 2026-06-15</ref>
* '''brother-udev-rule''': brother-udev-rule-type1-1.0.0-1.all.deb<ref>Google Drive: [https://drive.google.com/file/d/1f1HU-alOOYMbAI4fpRSMxaDHepVfAlsq/view?usp=drivesdk brother-udev-rule-type1-1.0.0-1.all.deb] retrieved 2026-06-15</ref>

=== If error out ===
If you encounter a GUI error reading "Error opening device: Invalid argument" unless you ran `gscan2pdf` as sudo, the udev rule generated by this package may have a defect on some systems where the SYSFS line isn't recognized.

Comment out the SYSFS line:
<pre>
sudo vi /etc/udev/rules.d/60-brother-libsane-type1.rules
</pre>
Then unplug or restart the device so it will re-read the rules.

== Features ==
The Brother ADS-2000 is a high-speed, high-volume desktop document scanner featuring:
* Two-sided (duplex) scanning
* 50-sheet Automatic Document Feeder (ADF)
* Scans documents, business cards, plastic ID cards, receipts, and photos up to 8.5" wide and 34" long.
* Multi-feed detection, background removal, blank page removal, and deskew support.

=== Scan to Destinations & Implementation ===
According to the device specifications, supported scan destinations include: E-mail, File, Image, OCR, USB flash memory drive, and Android devices. 

In the Pops KMS environment, we implement these logical destinations via the `brscan-skey` daemon. While the scanner itself may only have a single primary physical "Scan" button, the daemon handles the routing:

* '''Scan to Image''' (`IMAGE`): Implemented via a bash script (`scan_to_paperless.sh`) that automates batch-scanning directly into the Paperless-NGX consume directory.
* '''Scan to File''' (`FILE`): Implemented via a bash script (`scan_to_smb.sh`) that scans and outputs a PDF directly into the raw SMB documents folder (`/mnt/smb/share/Documents/Scans_Folder/`).
* '''Scan to OCR / E-mail''': Handled similarly via dedicated scripts defined in `/opt/brother/scanner/brscan-skey/brscan-skey-0.2.4-0.cfg`.

==== Desktop Shortcuts ====
To provide one-click push-to-scan capability without relying on the physical scanner buttons or the `brscan-skey` daemon, the `brother_scanner` Ansible playbook automatically provisions a `.desktop` shortcut directly to the user's desktop:
* '''Scan to SMB (Letter Duplex)''': Executes the `scan_to_smb.sh` script to trigger a two-sided (duplex), 150dpi, True Gray scan forced to US Letter geometry, saving the result directly to the raw SMB share.

